76561198073827099,Recommended,547900,27525093,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Spidermoon,"OverviewThis is the 8th edition of the Front Office Football franchise. It's a franchise that has come a long way and continues to impress more and more people. Much like the other mainstream text-based sports games, such as Football Manager and Out of the Park Baseball, it feels and plays much more intimately than a Madden Franchise mode. With that said, let's get into the review!Pros‣Real Players: The real names of players are included, and they are on their real teams.‣Customizable Players: You can customize their name, number, and even attempt to change their position.‣City Relocation: One of my personal favorite features is that there are a TON of cities that you are able to move your team to, but it isn't easy; you need to get a new stadium approved, which is hard to do in small cities. Other things are involved as well, such as the cities' other entertainment options and their desire for a team/closeness with other teams.‣City Growth: The cities, along with what was mentioned above,grow on their own.For example, the South could experience rapid growth, sparking a huge growth rate for the city of Orlando. In turn, this could lead the owners of the Jacksonville Jaguars to move to Orlando. The options are nearly endless.‣Playoff Chances: After Week 5 of the regular season, the game allows you to simulate the odds that the teams left in contention make the playoffs. This is a new feature from FOF7, and just adds even more value to this game.‣Endlessly Deep: The game is deeper than the Mariana Trench. In all seriousness, it has more realism than anything I've ever seen. You can design your own plays, set up your depth charts, and much, much more. You also have the option to leave all that to the AI and just focus on signing and managing the players. This deepness is a result of the hard work that the developer puts into each and every aspect of the game.‣Great Help Menu: The amount of depth of this game could and should leave you a little lost, but the help menu provided in game is incredible at explaining what everything is and how they all work. Give it a read.Cons‣Team Names: The teams do not have their real NFL names or logos. However, this is an easy fix due to an incredible community and the in-game team name changer.‣Crashes: If you play this game long enough, you will occasionally run into crashes. Not a big problem, just remember to click that save button!Final ThoughtsThis game is incredible. If you find yourself looking at this review, the odds are, you want this game. You will like it. If you are a football fan, there is a 100% chance you will like this game. Unfortunately, my team has less than a 0.1% chance to make the playoffs this year. Oh well, there's always the 2098 season!"
,Recommended,547900,28121129,"Posted: 1 December, 2016",all,msanderson313,"Your best outside linebacker is holding out.Sam has been good for your team in his three seasons, since you drafted him out of Florida State in the second round of the rookie draft. You thought he'd develop into a solid pass rusher -- and that came true. 6 sacks last season was third best on the team. But as training camp approaches, and your roster is starting to gel -- he thinks he's worth a raise. You look over his performance -- pass rush great, but he's only been so-so in coverage. You've got another guy who could play in the role, but Sam is better -- and he's better than anyone who you could find in free agency. But you have some gameplan ideas that might help use him effectively and limit his liabilities. He wants to be making $3 million a year -- and if you give him that money (with guaranteed bonuses) it might squeeze out your cap space to re-sign your game-changing tight end next year. You make the call... it might hurt to pay him this much, but he'll be angry if you don't pony up.Interested yet?THIS is the essence of Front Office Football. This isn't a button-mashing game. This isn't about absurd stats and silly power-ups. And this isn't a game which will test your graphics card. It's going to test your brains, your balls, and your gut instincts. This is a game where you... ""put yourself in the front office.""Your tools are scouting reports, rookie combine data, on-field statistics, and personality traits. Your decisions include salary cap management, roster-building, young player development, depth chart decisions, gameplan architecture, and finding value where others might miss it. Take on as much control as you want, turn over details to your hand-picked staff if you prefer. You can run the whole show, be just the GM, just the coach/gameplanner, or you can call the plays yourself in-game from a vast menu of options.Play a whole career, build your team in your own image, and tune your skills for a great challenge across a robust universe of multi-player leagues, with options to suit nearly anyone's tastes.If anything I'm describing above is what you're looking for in a football game... you owe it to yourself it play this one. FOF 8 takes a long tradition to a new level, and is a must-buy for the under-the-hood types who love the gridiron."
,Recommended,547900,27236402,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,Topper,"Here's the deal. This isn't a new game. It's the 8th iteration, modification, and improvement of the best American Football Franchise simulator around. A true indy, one man written and developed, you won't find fancy graphics or big budget presentation, but you will find statisical accuracy, the challenge of the draft, who to resign when your team runs up to the cap and all the frustration of running the Cleveland Browns franchise into the ground, year after year.New and rewritten for FOF 8  are playbooks for teams, along with thousands of playcalling combinations, personnel packages. You'll be able to import entire playbooks for your team, design your own plays, or let the AI handle all of that for you. You'll have to deal with contracts, inactive players, injuries,♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥off rookies who think they are really something special. You'll have to deal with career ending injuries, cap management, the challenge of trading players, draft picks, or all of the above for that shot at Ricky Williams (GO YOU!!!!)Players will boom and bust like in real life. You'll get to track their progress through training camps, and they'll need playing time if you want to get the develop quickly. The draft can be where you decide on who to fill out your roster with. There'll be players with skill but terrible combines, players with terrible skills who are amazing atheletes, and you'll eventually get a shot at players with the total package. How you manage all of that, who you draft, sign, trade will be totally up to you.The game will track the stats for all players, all teams, for the life of the game. You'll create a world all your own. The game is very deep. There isn't a pro football franchise simlulator with the kind of under the hood mechanincs that this one has. There are numerous ways to personalize the game through settings, like alternate player files, importing custom graphics, fog of war settings, and getting fired for sucking♥♥♥♥♥ Start the game with stock teams, a full draft, or a preference draft where you put emphasis on player groups and the scout does the drafting for you.If you didn't think that this was overwhelming enough, all this can be played against human managers in the many multiplayer leagues, some that have been going on for years and years, or new ones that are bound to start. There's no challenge like matching wits with human GM's in FOF. You're guaranteed to be humbled.Even though the help file and manual is robust, you can find answers to questions on the game, strategy, modifications and find a multi player league to join at Front Office Football Central, the unofficial home for all things FOF.http://www.operationsports.com/fofc/index.php"
