,Not Recommended,547900,28148777,"Posted: 2 December, 2016",all,Darkmatter,"Ignore previous positive review.  Developer believes Patch notes/Change Log are archaic and no longer necessary.  This tomfoolery has no place in PC Gaming.Seehttps://steamcommunity.com/app/547900/discussions/0/135507403157798555/xxxxxxxxSee I'm going to recommend this game with a caveat.  This game is not easy to pick up and learn, and the game does itself few favors in that regard.  The developer approaches the Interface in the same utilitarian way that ToadyOne, of DwarfFortress fame, approaches their UI: The UI is a means to display as much information as is possible, not necessarily as efficiently or as beautifully as possible.  But if you can look past the UI issues, you'll find probably the best Gridiron Management game out there.FOF8 has built upon FOF7's solid Owner/GM experience while fleshing out the playcalling and gameplanning for those of us who want to try their hand at coaching.  Now you have the ability to build an offensive playbook each year, filled with up to 200 different plays.  These plays can be made yourself or you can generate a given amount automatically, and each play has it's given style that can synergize with your Off. Coordinator's preferences.Once plays have been generated in your playbook, you'll need to actually build up a gameplan.  This too can be automated, a feature that you will probably avail yourself of if you're anything like me.  You see, on both sides of the ball you'll need to plug in plays for each possible situation.  1st and 10, 3rd and long, 3rd and One.  Ect.  However the current setup requires you to adjust 1 play at a time.  This adds up to alotof clicks.  This is by far my biggest gripe in an otherwise fantastic new feature.    Additionally, there are existing limitations to the # of unique plays in the playbook.  On defense it is 12, and on offense it is 50-60, depending on your Offensive Coordinator.  This system makes perfect since and is a fantastic way to add depth to your coaching choices.  However, in addition you are limited to around 80 plays in the gameplan in total.This makes absolutely no sense,especially on the defensive side of the ball.  Why the hell wouldn't the defense be able to remember the same 12 plays as often as they need to?Unfortunately because I play as a coach first, and a GM second, these issues have entirely ruined my experience.  Forcing myself to run with either a generated playbook that I have no investment in, or a hamstrung playbook that doesn't have the depth I need just makes me want to walk way from the computer.  As such, I've uninstalled the game until the developer can address these issues in the gameplanning system.Final ThoughtsThis game has a lot of progress to go before it's what most would consider 'polished', however it is already the absolute best Gridiron Management game on the market.  If you you are looking for a GM experience, and are ok leaving coaching to the game's AI, I am confident you will find yourself hooked.  However the new features in the coaching realm have hamstrung those of us who prefer to focus as much as possible on the day-to-day running of the team.  That said, the developer's history of releases also all but assures us that he will continue to support his product and address these flaws."
