,Recommended,547900,29345058,Posted: 18 January,all,ChadS,"I've been trying to decide how to best review this game for newcomers.  I've finally decided with the following.FOF8 is my first version of this franchise.  I'm a long time gamer, programmer, sports simulation enthusiast, etc.The Good:FOF8 is a pretty darn good game.  It gives you some flexibility in building a team, and managing it.  There's some opportunity to call plays, as well, which can add a layer of depth to the game for some.  The bulk of the game, though, is dealing with your roster and improving your team.Overall, it's what most people want from a sports sim that does not have a graphical component--it's a number-crunching engine, and produces reasonable statistics, for the most part.  The hardest part is managing your salary cap.  The second hardest is managing your injuries.  I found the injuries to be a little to frequent with the default setting, and dialed them back each year until I got to something I thought was about normal.The Bad:Many of these are tiny issues.  There's very little ""flash"" or ""pop"" to the presentation of the game.  It's very similar to looking at a bunch of spreadsheets.  Some of the ""cool factors"" that are added (Green Sheet, Grey Sheet, Scouting Report, etc.) don't feel like they add as much flavor as they could.  Some features aren't properly documented, and some things that feel like they should be no brainers aren't in therePerhaps my biggest beef with the game comes when I'm calling plays.  First, I don't sense much effect with regards to calling plays.  I can call for a deep route on 3rd and 20, or on 2nd and 1, and it feels like defenses cover it the same.Also, it feels as though virtually every 3rd down play is successful.  I had a spell of 8 games where my (undefeated) team only stopped opponents on 8% of their 3rd down attempts.  It didn't matter if it was 3rd and 4, or 3rd and 25, the opponent almost always got 4 yards more than they needed.  Even after drastically improving my defense, this continued (although, the opponents success rate did fall toward, but not into, more normal ranges).  In short, I have the league leading defense in yards per play, yards per run, and yards per pass, but I can't stop a 3rd down, almost ever.I gave up play-calling for that reason.  I strictly manage the team and the rosters now.One other little thing--12 year veteran lineman will try to get you to sign them to 4 year multi-million dollar deals pretty regularly.  I don't know how realistic that is.Finally, if you are in playcalling mode, there's no way to change your personnel packages.  You can't sit your awesome QB in the 4th quarter of a late season game to keep him healthy for the playoffs.  Packages are set from game to game, and I have yet to see a backup get playing time, outside of pre-season.  That makes it pretty hard to nurture your up-and-coming first round QB pick.Otherwise:The game is fun, if not perfect.  There does seem to be tendencies for players to resign with you when they have high loyalty, for example.  Most players want unservicable salaries after a couple of years, and you end up with decisions to make.  Every once in a while you'll find a veteran that's willing to renegotiate to lower your current cap problems, so you can bring in someone new.  Even superstars are hard to trade if they have a big contract.The game doesn't really tell you what you're doing wrong.  It will tell you what positions you need help at, but it's not specific at all.  I had a situation where I had what I thought were good D-linemen, but I was getting killed in the running game.  It would be nice if the assistant coach might say, ""we need some run-stopper linebackers,"" or something to help me figure out, ""oh, I'm getting owned in the gaps.""I hope this was helpful, and I hope you enjoy the game!"
76561198060675837,Recommended,547900,30775874,Posted: 27 March,all,jamie.santavy,"Personally I give this game an 8/10 in terms of how close it comes to what the game sets out to achieve and what I believe most players are expecting. I started playing FoF 7 a few years ago and I've been hooked ever since. If there's something I really have to stress to anyone on the fence about buying this game who has never played Front office Football before it's that this game isn't for everyone. This game is for people who are looking for the most in depth football text sim, this game has a steep learning curve, and requires a solid time investment to be successful. For those who already own FOF7 I don't feel like there was enough added to the game to justify buying FOF8 outside of the fact that most MP leagues have moved on to FOF8Some features of the game-Full Multiplayer leagues. In my opinion this is the #1 reason to buy the game. The SP mode can be fun but in any game like this when you learn enough it becomes a little too easy to beat the AI with consistent success. There are several active MP leagues in FOF8 who are regularly changing ownership and accept players of any skill level. Competing against a full league of other owners is a worthy challenge and makes all stages of the game much more interesting.Offense:-Full control of depth chart by formation-Full control of offensive playbook. You can either generate plays tied to your Offensive Coordinator's philosophy, or you can create all your plays yourself. This allows you to create your own route concepts in the passing game. Playbooks can hold up to 200 plays and you can save playbooks if you want to use them season to season-Full control of your weekly offensive gameplan. The amount of plays you can use depends on your OC again and allows you to set which plays you want to be called in which situation. Game planning can be tough but gives the player control over your offensive style.Defense-A wealth of defensive styles available-Weekly game plans allow you to play your defense to your team's strengths-Gives the player control over how often your defense blitzes, plays man / zone, or bump and run coverage. Also has formations that bring the safety into the box for a stronger run defense.Roster Management / Drafting-A fairly complex system where player ratings aren't everything and much like the NFL there are underrated players who find in game success and high rated players who under perform.-Player ratings that are never perfect. The game uses your coaches' scouting ability to determine the ratings you see, a player's true rating can differ fairly significantly from the ratings you see. The more years a player has been in the league the closer your scouted ratings will be to a players true rating.-A draft system that is truly more of an art than a science. You're not going to find your 6th round Tom Brady but for those who are willing to put the time in you can start to identify solid role players deep into the draft.-A contract negotiation system that is tied to player production as well as skill. Unproven players or players who have under performed recently will sign for a discount. Low-average rated players who have impressive seasons statistically will demand more money.-Player hold outs and satisfaction. Some players who feel underpaid will hold out of the preseason for a better contract. Other players may become unhappy due to lack of starting time or because they have a conflict with another player. Unhappy players may refuse to sign with a team altogether.Cons/Criticisms-The UI. Personally I find it manageable / tolerable but I have seen many people complain about the UI over my time on the FOFC forums and feel it should be mentioned that this is something some people really don't care for.-Lack of control in more subtle ways. There's no such thing as a ""zone run"" scheme, no such thing as bringing a 6th OL in as a TE, and no way to put your TE in the slot unless you play him as a slot WR in a certain formation. Also you cannot choose which player will be blitzing from a defensive formation altough you can influence it to more often be your best pass rusher.-The game seems to favor the short passing game / screen game over throwing the ball 10-15 yards down the field. (opinion)-Running backs can get way more touches in a season than would be realistic if they have high enough endurance."
